voice_to_text: Do you have to feed your cats a wet food only diet for them to live a long, happy and healthy life? I normally don't make reaction videos like this, but I just felt. I felt like it. I felt like it today and I post on TikTok, so here I am. No disrespect to this vet at all, I just wanna share a couple thoughts that I have. Um, number one, this video was made in reaction to the video of a very sweet person talking about how her cat passed away and her vet told her that wet food would have helped prevent it. So one thing is to keep in mind that the idea that wet food could have helped prevent this passing was from a vet. It wasn't from like a random person. Secondly, I think it's disappointing that there's this idea that people who talk about nutrition on social media whatever, including vets who talk about it, are trying to guilt trip others or make them feel bad for feeding kibble. I don't think that's the intention of most people. I know a lot of wonderful creators that are just trying to share information to help people and help pets. Not everyone is trying to guilt trip someone. Um, in addition, it's really important to note that no one, or at least most people, don't think nutrition is a one way ticket to perfect health. Nutrition is one factor in health, just like a healthy Human can, like, eat a perfect diet and still get sick. But nutrition is within the owner's control. It is our responsibility to feed our pets. We can't control genetics, but we can control what our cats consume. So I don't think nutrition's role in health should be negated. And again, the most important thing that you can do, or the best thing that you can do is get information from a ton of different sources. There are plenty of vets on this app talking about the basics of cat nutrition, like the fundamental biology that cats are needing high moisture, high protein diets. So you can talk to different vets while differing opinions. You can talk to people who study nutrition. You can read books, try to get a wealth of information, come to your own conclusions, because there's really not one source of truth. And I know it's confusing and it sucks, but just try to absorb as much information as you can. And whether your opinions ultimately go with this person or air more on the fresh feeding, wet food, you know, it's your pet and you're making choices for them.
